 and political and military discourses, suggest the variety of forces competing for-or commanding-attention in the period. This new framework for interpreting Romanticism and its legacy illuminates what turns out to be an ongoing tradition of war literature that, rather than give testimony to or represent warfare, uses rhythm and verse to experiment with how and what we attend to during times of war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAttentionzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aAuthors and readerszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnglish poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoetics. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aRomanticism. 4aalarmism. 4aattention. 4adiscipline. 4amilitarization. 4aobservation. 4apoetics. 4apoetry and politics. 4avigilance. 4awar literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804798761zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798761.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles